<p><b>Torture;   
</b></p>
<p> 
Alleged forcible return of six ethnic Uighurs to the People&#8216;s Republic of 
</p>
<p>China. According to the information received, on 31 December 2012, the 
Malaysian police secretly transferred six asylum seekers into the custody of 
Chinese authorities who brought them back to the People&#8216;s Republic of 
</p>
<p>China on a chartered flight. Their asylum claims were reportedly still 
pending. It is reported that the Chinese Government frequently accuses 
ethnic Uighurs, particularly those seeking asylum, of being terrorists or 
separatists without providing evidence to substantiate such claims. Ethnic 
Uighurs who have been active in overseas political or human rights 
activities and who apply for asylum allegedly face a heightened risk of 
human rights violations, including torture if they return or are forcibly 
returned to the People&#8216;s Republic of China. 
