<p>Alleged imposition of the death penalty on a community activist. According 
to the information received, in 2009, Mr. Bakri Moussa Mohammed, a 
community activist in the Kalma camp for displaced people in South Darfur 
was arrested. Moreover, Mr. Moussa Mohammed was sentenced in 2010 to 
10 years of imprisonment for alleged participation in a murder, in retaliation 
for his activism. On 31 December 2012, an officer of the Kober prison in 
Khartoum informed Mr. Moussa Mohammed, that his punishment had been 
revised to a death sentence. Subsequently, he was transferred to death row. 
The same day, he was reportedly brought to the gallows three times, before 
being told that the execution would be postponed for 35 days. It is reported 
that there was no hearing about this change of sentence and that Mr. Moussa 
Mohammed could be executed at any moment. It is alleged that the decision 
was taken by the prison administration under pressure from the National 
Security Service. 
